description.value: Glazed composition figurine of a male figure. Kneeling man wearing a schenti in the offering pose, presenting a jar. The figure holds lid with right hand, while left hand rests on thigh, and kneels on rectangular base, without back pillar.  The jar is a two-handled one, a small amphora, with eared handles on either side and a flat lid.  Main outlines crudely modelled with blade.   Face with triangular shape, projecting eyes, and large ears, with hands without fingers,  and only thumb indicated on left hand. Suspension loop pushed  through below hair line at back. The glaze has faded to off-white, with greenish tinge indicating originally green? Black-brown secondary glaze applied on hair, on top of amphora, and on right handle,  and in thick band on hem of skirt.

description.value: Limestone figure of a bound prisoner, the arms by the sides of the body but lashed at the elbows behind the back. The legs are doubled up from the knees behind the body, to allow the feet to be caught under the same binding. The carving is crude with planes of working showing in the soft limestone, although the face of this example, especially the eyes, is better done. The figure wears a headdress in the style of a cap or hood with a ridge in the centre, falling down at the back to the base of the neck.

description.value: Fragment of a statuette of a king as sphinx: the head and part of one shoulder of a king as sphinx moulded, in opaque turquoise-blue glass, glossy surface. The representation was traditional with the nemes headdress, beard strap, and beard and the fine incised pattern invariably found on the withers. An identifying inscription was undoubtedly incised on the front of the body now lost. The uraeus is of the slender, undulating type extending over the crown of the head. The fine   details were doubtless formed in the mould but were extensively retooled after removal from the mould.

description.value: Wooden striding figure of Meryrahashtef: the figure shows the subject as a young man, probably in his teens. It is carved from a single piece of ebony and mounted on a simple base of sycamore wood. The form is conventional: the young man is shown, rather exceptionally, in the nude, striding forward, his left leg advanced, his arms at his sides, fists clenched, holding truncated cylindrical objects which have been identified as small rolls of cloth. The head is covered with the conventional curled wig, very carefully carved and painted black, and the eyes, which in a superior commission would have been inlaid, are simply painted. The delineation of the facial details is sensitive and restrained: the eyebrows are lightly indicated, the nose subtly modeled, the unemphasized mouth slightly unbalanced, suggesting a wry smile.

description.value: Terracotta figure of female harpist.  An upper part broken from a figure of a woman celebrant, probably standing. Her hair is parted in the middle and she wears a tightly woven and bound wreath, with more of her headdress above broken away. The strap of her chiton has slipped off her left shoulder, and she holds and plays a triangular harp placed high on her right side. The back of the figure is lost.  Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous brown Nile silt with a grey core. The horizontal and upright elements of the harp are painted yellow, and the wreath and the chiton have minute traces of pink paint.
